Besides the poems represented in this volume, Ovid was the author of the Ars Amatoria and the Remedium Amoris (to which reference has just been made), and oi numerous “Elegies,” including tour books oi letters written in exile (Ex Ponto Libri iv.). As a poet, his lame is tar below that of Virgil and Horace, - deservedly‚ since his loose and easy verse bears no comparison with the elaborate finish oi theirs. For fancy and fine poetic feeling, however, many of the Elegies - both in the Tristia and the Amores- show a vein of as good quality as either oi his rivals; while in absolute, ease oi handling the artificial structure οἳ Latin verse it may be doubted whether he has ever had an equal. His chief merit, however, is as an excellent story-teller,—smooth, facile, fluent, sometimes, it must be contessed, inordinately diffuse. As the most celebrated existing collection oi the most famous iables oi the ancient world, the Metmomhoses, in particular, makes the best oi introductions to the nobler and more difficult verse oi Virgil.
